{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502594"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:46:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:46:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1878"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1878"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.12,0.05,0.39,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1878"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112620"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1878"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1878"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94650"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3525"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13861"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15661"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18508"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34003"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36566"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36567"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46228"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112620"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 61-year-old woman presents to her family practitioner after an episode of left iliac fossa pain 2 days ago which resolved spontaneously after three hours. She has no other symptoms. Her medical history is unremarkable She does not use any medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she looks well, with a blood pressure of 115/75 mmHg, pulse 82/min and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft, with no abnormal findings. A CT scan is arranged (Images 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What does the CT show?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A normal examination","Renal cyst","Renal tumour","Adrenal adenoma","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIt can be questioned as to why a CT was done in this case and what were the indications for such a procedure. However, in the real world and in current medical practice, many unnecessary investigations are performed - particularly imaging investigations. With regards to CT scanning, in the 1980\u0027s there were about three million CT scans performed annually in the United States. That figure now exceeds 93 million scans a year, with little increase in the population. The reason for the dramatic increase is not clear, but probably relates to increased availability of CT scanning and clinician-dependance. Despite the advantages of good diagnostic yield, there are unexpected consequences and these include increased cancer risks from radiation exposure and the \u0027incidentaloma.\u0027 This term was coined to describe incidental findings on scanning that were unrelated to what lead to the scan being performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne of the commonest incidental findings on abdominal CT scanning is an adrenal abnormality. This CT scans shows a right-sided \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal tumour\u003C/strong\u003E (Image). It is estimated that some form of adrenal abnormality will be detected in about 5% of adult abdominal CTs. This is about the same as the prevalence of such adrenal masses being found at autopsy - thus raising the question of what to do about these incidentalomas - apart from causing anxiety on the part of the patient. In this case the size of the adenoma warrants further investigation - and this should start with endocrine function studies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe commonest mode of \u0027presentation\u0027 of renal neoplasms is now an incidental finding on an imaging study. Likewise, few gastrointestinal stromal tumours cause symptoms and most come to light as incidental radiological findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe normal structures that can be seen on these two images include the liver, spleen, gallbladder and both kidneys. The adrenal tumour is clearly visible on the axial view.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adrenal masses are common incidental findings on radiological studies."],"references":["Kebebew E. Adrenal Incidentaloma. N Engl J Med 2021; 384:1542-51. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33882207/","https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33882207/","Fassnacht M, Tsagarakis S, Terzolo M, et al. European Society of Endocrinology clinical practice guidelines on the management of adrenal incidentalomas, in collaboration with the European Network for the Study of Adrenal Tumors. Eur J Endocrinol. 2023 Jul 20;189(1):G1-G42. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37318239/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94650"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1878"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17144"},{"type":"media","id":"17145"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21848"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17144"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7404e0bc-8f76-4db3-8fdc-137a63611cc6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7404e0bc-8f76-4db3-8fdc-137a63611cc6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":539,"height":590}},{"type":"media","id":"17145"